The "Coeur d'Alene Basin Restoration Act of 1994" is cited in this Act. It amends Title I of the Federal Water Pollution Control Act by adding a section for the Coeur d'Alene Basin Management Conference. The Coeur d'Alene Basin Management Conference is established to develop a pollution prevention and restoration plan. The conference includes members from the EPA, Coeur d'Alene Indian tribe, and Idaho Department of Environmental Quality. Steering committees are appointed for management and technical advisory roles. The Management Conference for the Coeur d'Alene Basin includes a technical advisory committee, citizens' advisory committee, and ex officio members. They are responsible for publishing a pollution prevention, control, and restoration plan within a year of enactment. The plan will clarify the duties of Federal and State entities. The plan for the Coeur d'Alene Basin Management Conference will clarify duties for Federal and State agencies in water pollution prevention and control, describe funding methods, incorporate environmental management concepts, and include a strategy for water pollution. The Plan for the Coeur d'Alene Basin Management Conference includes a strategy for water pollution prevention and control, promoting pollution prevention practices. The Administrator will approve the Plan after public review and comment. Upon approval of the Plan by the Administrator, it will be considered an approved management program under section 319(h) and a comprehensive conservation and management plan under section 320 of the Act. Grant assistance may be provided for the development of the Plan, including research. The Plan development assistance includes research, surveys, studies, and technical work. Grants cover up to 70% of costs with a requirement for non-Federal funding. The Administrator can set terms and conditions. The 'Coeur d'Alene Basin' is defined as the watershed in northern Idaho. The Coeur d'Alene Basin in northern Idaho includes the South Fork of the Coeur d'Alene River, the main stem of the Coeur d'Alene River, and Lake Coeur d'Alene. This section does not affect the jurisdiction of any US or State department or agency, or any entity related to the Basin created by treaty. The Environmental Protection Agency is authorized to receive necessary funds for fiscal years 1995-1999. SEC. 3. FEDERAL PROGRAM COORDINATION. The United States Geological Survey of the Department of the Interior will enhance data collection in the Coeur d'Alene Basin by developing an integrated geographic information system and converting recording sites to monitoring stations with full gauging capabilities. The United States Geological Survey will establish additional monitoring stations in the Coeur d'Alene Basin for data collection and monitoring, including ground water mapping and water quality assessment. The Secretary of the Interior, in cooperation with the Fish and Wildlife Service, will implement a fisheries resources conservation program. The Coeur d'Alene Basin will establish a fisheries restoration program and conduct a wildlife species and habitat survey, including endangered species assessments. The Coeur d'Alene Basin will establish a fisheries restoration program and conduct a wildlife species and habitat survey, including endangered species assessments. The Director of the United States Fish and Wildlife Service is authorized to carry out activities related to improving the health of fishery resources, conducting investigations about the status of fishery resources, and periodically updating a survey of migratory bird populations within the basin. The Coeur d'Alene Basin will establish a fisheries restoration program and conduct a survey of fishery resources and habitats. Appropriations are authorized for fiscal years 1995-1999 to support these activities. SEC. 4. RESTORATION PLAN. The Secretary of the Interior, through the Bureau of Land Management, will develop a restoration plan for public lands in the Coeur d'Alene Basin to reduce human and environmental risks. This includes creating a geographical information system inventory of abandoned mining sites and contaminated areas. The plan includes cleanup of mining contaminated sites, restoration of natural resources, stream and river restoration plans, monitoring of restored areas, and cooperation with other land managing entities in the Basin. (6) Develop and implement a land management plan with various agencies and stakeholders to reduce health and environmental risks in the Basin.
(7) Create and maintain a computerized system for cultural and ecological resources, contaminated areas, and restoration activities for coordinated management.
(8) Collaborate with wildlife agencies and interests to develop habitat management plans for streams and rivers in the Basin. (9) Implement monitoring of wildlife management areas in the Basin to assess effectiveness of improvements and restoration activities;
(10) Collaborate with various agencies and stakeholders to develop an integrated public recreation management plan for the Basin, focusing on minimizing health risks and providing public information;
(11) Establish a lake and river information program in the Basin to offer public use and health risk information, alongside recreation management and maintenance. The Director of the United States Bureau of Land Management is authorized to carry out activities related to data collection, inventory of mining waste source areas, contaminated lands, resource information management, restoration activities, monitoring data, accepting or acquiring mining contaminated lands for restoration, design, construction, and maintenance of restoration projects and facilities. The Bureau of Land Management is authorized to oversee the construction and management of repositories for mine waste, provide lake and river information, develop restoration and land management plans, and maintain restored public lands. Appropriations are authorized for fiscal years 1995-2002 to carry out these activities. SEC. 5. EXEMPTION FROM CERCLA LIABILITY. The EPA and DOI are exempt from liability under CERCLA for actions taken under this Act.
